#####################################################################################################
Version 1.3 
    version note (July 17 2009):
		(1) This version adopts a user-friendly input and output.
		(2) Tree calculation adopts the double-precision accuracy.
		(3) There is no limitation on the CPU number and one-dimensional 
			grid number.
		(4) A routine to find the best value of seed number which can 
			generate the best simulated power spectrum. For this test, 
			the iseed number should be set positive in the input parameter file.
Version 1.2 
	version note:
		(1) This version adopts the double precision accuracy for 
			the simulation particles (-DXYZDBL). It operates in a single 
			precision but retains the double precision accuracy after all.
		(2) The orginal particle type is
			typedef struct pmparticletype {
				float x,y,z,vx,vy,vz;
				indextype indx;
			}
			where (x,y,z) is the position vector. But if XYZDBL option is set, 
			(x,y,z) is the offset vector from its Lagrangian point.
		(3) If XYZDBL compile option is set in, the output particle data 
			adopt the offset vector (xoffset, yoffset, zoffset) rather than the 
			typical position vector. In order to obtain the position of a 
			particle from the offset vector p->(x,y,z),
				x = fmod(p->x + (p->indx%( nx/nspace)            )*nspace+nx,nx)
				y = fmod(p->y + (p->indx%((nx/nspace)*(ny/nspace))*nspace+ny,ny)
				z = fmod(p->z + (p->indx/((nx/nspace)*(ny/nspace))*nspace+nz,nz)
		where nx, ny, and nz is the mesh size in the x, y, and z direction.
Version 1.1 
	version note (April 19, 2009): 
		(1) This version of GOTPM is utilizing the CAMB package to generate 
			the initial power spectrum. A flag whether to read or generate 
			power spectrum is in the 10'th line of the parameter file, 
			"params.dat". - 14/Nov/08
		(2) It still uses the single precision accuracy.
		(3) Binary files of the power spectrum should have the same 
			version of camb libraries, or it fails.
		(4) External ascii file is read to input the inflation power 
			while the transfer function should be provided by the CAMB (Source).

##################################
##################################
Source Files : 
##################################

	Make-related FILES:
		Makefile: main script for makefile
		Rules.make: some compilation rules and options.

	SOURCE CODES:
		namu.c: main body of the code
		ZeldovichInit.F: parallel PMSEED using force array 
		mysub.f90: subroutines to use  camb packages to generate 
			the power spectrum or read from outside
		fda4.c: 4-point FDA force calculation in the PM part 
		tsc.c: TSC density measures in PM part 
		correl.F: Calculation of the correlation in PM part 
		pmigrate.c: a routine for particle migration between parallel nodes.
		p_solver.F: Poisson solver in PM part 
		pm_main_sub.F: FFTW related subroutines 
		Memory2.c: memory administration part
		timerutil.c: time check routines 
		VarPM.c: a mesh-communication routine for variable-height PM domains 
		slicemigrate.c: for the migration of slices between parallel nodes 
		savexzslice.c: a subroutine to save density slabs 
		flagwriting.c: a subroutine to check when to dump whole particle 
			data on disks
		force_spline.c: generating the correction values that will be 
			used by the tree jobs 
		Treewalk.c: routines for tree build and walks  
		mydomaindecomposition.c: an efficient domain-decomposition algorithm 
		lightcone.c: a subroutine to save lightcone data 
		kjhrw.c: a subroutine to dump whole particle data 
		sub.lynx.camb.F: many subroutines used by the PMSEED 
		kjhtpm.c: main body of the TREE jobs 
		indexing.c: a routine to decide the particle index 
		FindSeed.F: a routine to find the best seed number

	Main Parameter File:
		(1) Type "make misc" to generate "mkpfile.exe" which makes 
			the default parameter file.
	    (2) Generate default parameter file: use mkpfile.exe
		(3) The simulation parameters can be set as 
			"define [parameter] = [value]".
				- A line starting with "#" is assumed to be a comment.
				- rvfilename and rvprefix should be "INITIAL" at the 
					starting of the simulation.
				- Nx, Ny, and Nz should be same.
				- Powerflag can have three values, 0, 1, and 2
				  0: do not read power spectrum. Instead, generate 
				  the power spectrum with CAMB Source
				  1: read the power spectrum file whose name is written 
				  right after this flag. In this case, "Powerfile" should be set.
				  2: read the transfer file and use the input ascii power file.
				     The ascii power file should consist of two columns, k and P(k).


    How to generate the power spectrum by the stand-alone command.
		(1) Type "make misc", then you can get viewpower.exe and 
		mkpower.exe commands.
		(2) Type "mkpower.exe params.dat", then you can get a power 
			spectrum file of the same name as written in the "params.dat". 
			The cosmological model of the generated power spectrum is 
			also given by the "params.dat"
		(3) Type "viewpower.exe input_PS_file" gives you the basic 
			information of the model parameters and power spectrum (k and P(k)).

	How to generate the path of the point of view of observers.
		(1) Type "make misc", then you can get mktrack.exe command file.
		(2) Create the "initial viewer file"
		(3) Run mktrack.exe to generate the simulation readable file.

	Flow-controlling FILES:
		(1) "Suddenstop.flag": a flag file to indicate when to stop or 
			to save backup files. The "\pm" sign after number
			indicates whether to proceed further ("+") or stop 
			("-", respectively). If another character is given, it stops 
			without dumping any backup file.
		(2) Generally the backup file names are "INITIAL.#####*****" 
		    and "params.#####" where ##### is five digits of step 
			number and ***** is five digits of parallel node number.
		(3) "WriteSync&WholeDen.flag": a file containing redshifts numbers
		    when to save whole synchronized, power spectrum, and density data.
####################
####################
How to Run:
####################
    MANUAL STARTING:
	(1) To begin the simulation:
	    mpirun -np #_of_processors -machinefile $machinefilename -nolocal namu.exe params.dat

	(2) To restart from backup file (ex. with step number "101". There should be params.00101 file): 
		mpirun -np #_of_processors -machinefile $machinefilename -nolocal namu.exe params.00101 

    SCRIPT STARTING:
####################
####################
Compilers: mpif77, mpicc, and F90 are needed. F90 is for the CAMB package.
####################

####################
####################
Compilation options:
####################

	COMFLAGS:
		-DINDEX: padding "index" to the particle structure (mandatory)
		-DVarPM: admission of variable size of local domain slabs (mandatory)
		
	FDFLAGS:
		-DINCLUDE_TREE_FORCE: including tree correction  (mandatory)
		-DEH98: using power spectrum of Eisenstein & Hu (1998). If not set, then CAMB Source
                        is used to derive the power spectrum

	CDFLAGS:
		-DNMEG=3720L: the maximum size of memory for each node (in Megabytes).
			Here character "L" should be attached after digital number to declare 
			the long integer type.
		-DCORRELATION_FUNCTION: a flag to measure the correlation (optional ?)
		-DINCLUDE_TREE_FORCE: for tree correction (mandatory)
		-D_LARGE_FILES: to access large-size files (> 4GB) particularly in linux boxes
		-DSAVESLICE: a flag for saving density slabs (optional but strongly recommended)
			Usually the program saves x-z density slab (collective densities of three slabs
			at y=0, 1, 2) for each time step.
		-DPMSEEDFORCE: using the force array to measure velocities in the PMSEED part
			(mandatory)
		-DLAM: LAM-MPI option for the program argument issue (in quest it is not necessary)
		-DDEBUG: a flag for printing out huge messages for foolish debugging (optional)
		-DXYZDBL: a flag to use index for the double precision of the particle position.

